muscarinic receptors","Inhibits mast cell degranulation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of theophylline is \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of phosphodiesterase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to increased levels of cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) within cells, particularly in bronchial smooth muscle, resulting in bronchodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking leukotriene receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of montelukast and other leukotriene receptor antagonists. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta-2 agonists like salbutamol work by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of muscarinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in anticholinergic bronchodilators like ipratropium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne mechanism of cromones like sodium cromoglicate is the \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of mast cell degranulation\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETheophylline also has anti-inflammatory effects and may enhance respiratory muscle function. Due to its narrow therapeutic window and potential for toxicity, it is now used less frequently than newer bronchodilators.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Theophylline acts primarily by inhibiting phosphodiesterase, which leads to increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate levels.","Theophylline causes bronchodilation through smooth muscle relaxation and has anti-inflammatory effects.","The therapeutic window of theophylline is narrow, requiring careful monitoring of blood levels."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T09:31:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:22:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65954"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t